HEADWORD: Dianoetic
<hw>Di`a*no*et"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/;
<grk>dia`</grk> through + <?/ to revolve in the mind.]</ety>
<fld>(Metaph.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to the discursive faculty, its acts
or products.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I would employ . . . <qex>dianoetic</qex> to denote the operation
of the discursive, elaborative, or comparative faculty.</q> <rj><qau>Sir
W. Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Dianoialogy</ent>⟦br⟧
